multithreading  is a mechanism of dividing the CPU time between multiple threads.
A thread is a lightweight sub-process, the smallest unit of processing.

Multitasking is being achieved in two ways :
Multiprocessing : Process-based multitasking
- heavyweight process and occupies different address spaces in memory.

Multithreading : Thread-based multitasking
- lightweight process and occupies the same address space.

Threads are Independent
Threads are individual sequences of execution.
Each thread can execute its tasks independently of other threads.
They can run concurrently (parallel execution if the CPU has multiple cores or through time slicing on a single core).
Threads can have their own stack, which contains local variables, method call details, and other temporary data unique to the thread.
Threads share the process's heap memory and static variables.

2. Sharing the Same Address Space
Address space refers to the memory allocated to a program by the operating system.
When a program runs, it is given a specific area of memory that contains:
Code: The instructions of the program.
Heap: Memory for objects and dynamically allocated variables.
Static/Global Memory: Memory for static variables and global variables.
Stack: Separate stacks for each thread to store temporary/thread-local data.

Sharing the same address space allows threads to:

++
Communicate efficiently: Threads can directly access shared objects in the heap without the overhead of inter-process communication.
Work collaboratively: Threads can update shared state or data structures for tasks like computations, file processing, etc.

--
Sharing the same address space also introduces risks:

Data Races: If two threads try to modify the same shared variable at the same time, it can lead to inconsistent or incorrect results.
Deadlocks: If threads are waiting on each other to release resources, the program can freeze.
Synchronization Overhead: To prevent data races, synchronization techniques (like locks or thread-safe classes) are needed, which can slow down performance.
